    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl>Morelli in <ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>223</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>103120</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#parisipresicce2007a"/>, p. <citedRange>498</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
              </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                            <ab>
                                <lb n="1"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Eutimia"><name nymRef="#Εὐτιμία">Εὐτιμία</name></persName>
                            </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Eutimia.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Eutimia.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Eutimia.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Morelli's reading is puzzling both because of the nominative instead of the usual genitive and of the oddity of the presumed divine name.
                No other altar in the Sanctuary of Apollo is dedicated to an abstract entity considered a deity. Even Panakeia has a 'personal' flare, being 
                said daughter of Asklepios. The only similar case would be the altar of Eunomia on the Agora (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr083800</ref>), the placement of which seems to be more easy to 
                explain in relation with the political life.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
